<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25141k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25141k">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25141k"> 141(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bride&apos;s lament proxy</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Silent and alone, with head bent sadly down, she stood in the middle of the room till asked if she were willing &ldquo;To marry this man?&rdquo; when, without looking up, she answered &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; <p>Then the <mark>&ldquo;weeping woman&rdquo; who is hired</mark> for such occasions&mdash;just as in days, happily gone by, English families used to hire mutes for funerals&mdash;put her arm round the bride&apos;s waist, and, with bowed head, swinging her body to and fro the while, began in a most melancholy voice to <mark>sing &ldquo;The Bride&apos;s Lament</mark> to her Home.&rdquo;</p> <small> Mrs Alec Tweedie, <a name="TTFC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TTFC"><cite title="source">Through Finland in Carts</cite></a> (1914) 137-8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14090l" href="c14all.htm#c14090l">VI.C.14:090(l)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
